voice_to_text: It's an oh shit moment where you realized you've been doing something the wrong way for years. I worked at the same insurance office for almost 10 years. Every single morning I'd stop at Jerry's Coffee on Fifth Street, order my usual black coffee and add what I thought was cream from the self serve station. My co workers always made fun of how strong and bitter my coffee was. They take one sip and make faces like I was drinking motor oil. How do you drink that garbage? My best mate Ashley would say watching me gulp down my morning cup. I just laugh and tell her I liked my coffee with character, strong and bold, just like me. The whole office knew about my weird coffee preference. Even during meetings, people would joke about how I could probably strip paint with whatever I was drinking. For almost a decade, this was my routine. Same coffee shop, same order, same weird looks from everyone who tried it. I thought I just had different taste buds or something. Maybe I was just tougher than everyone else when it came to bitter drinks. And one Tuesday morning, Jerry's Coffee was closed for kitchen repairs. A handwritten sign on the door said they'd be back in a week. I panicked a little because I'm not great with change. But I spotted another coffee place just two blocks down called bean. There I walked in and ordered my usual black coffee. Please, the young Barista with purple hair smiled and handed me the cup. Then I asked for cream on the side, just like I always did at Jerry's. We'd only met twice before, but she seemed pretty cool and I figured it might help us get to know each other better. Fast forward to three weeks ago. We drove to Jason's hometown to visit his family and talk wedding stuff. His brother Greg, Greg's wife Monica and Avery came over to his parents house. Second I saw Avery, I noticed something different. She was wearing baggy cargo pants, an oversized hoodie, and her hair was pulled back in a messy bun, way more casual than the last time I'd seen her in a floral sundress. We sat in the living room drinking coffee and Jason's mom brought out wedding magazines. She started flipping through pages of bridesmaid dresses, pointing at the puffy ones and the sparky ones. Avery shifted in her seat. Her shoulders got tense. She stopped making eye contact with anyone. Monica noticed, oh, we'll have to take you shopping soon, honey. Get you something pretty and feminine. For once, she laughed like it was a joke. But Avery's face went red. Jason's mom chimed in, yes, and maybe we can do something with your hair. A nice updo would look so lovely. Greg nodded. It'll be good for you to dress up. You're at that age where you should be presenting yourself better. I watched Avery sink deeper into the couch. She pulled her hoodie sleeves over her hands. Then Monica said it. It'll be nice to see you dressed like a girl for once. My stomach dropped. I was a total tomboy growing up, hated dresses, hated makeup. voice_to_text: To escape from the police, Eddie parachuted down into a desert. In the next second, the parachute sank into his body. It was Venom, Eddie, his best partner. Venom gave Eddie superhuman abilities, but also made him a target for the police. Venom warned Eddie that an unknown creature was approaching them. They had to leave quickly. But Venom thought running on foot was far too slow. Suddenly, Eddie spotted a horse in the desert. It was their best option. Eddie approached the horse, and Venom quickly took control of its body. With the boost of its dark power, the horse could reach speeds of 500 kilometers per hour. They dashed across the desert at incredible speed. After two hours of running, Venom stopped by a river to rehydrate. But the police had already locked onto their location. Soldiers blasted Venom with a powerful sonic wave. The frightened horse threw Eddie into the water. Venom immediately jumped in after him. But the soldiers weren't planning to let them go. One soldier tried to trap venom with a fishing net. But Venom escaped effortlessly. Eddie hoped to use the river to get rid of the pursuers. But he didn't know there was a cliff just 100 meters ahead. At the critical moment, Venom took over Eddie's body again. It wanted to save Eddie's life. But doing so would throw them into even greater danger. The Venom Hunters had already found their location.

video_description: My parents were furious when they learned we bought a new house and called a selfish, so my husband threw them out.
voice_to_text: My parents were furious when they Learned we bought a new house and called a selfish. So my husband threw them out. But what they said next changed everything. My parents always treated me like the family servant while my brother got everything. Growing up, I'd mow lawns while he played video games. I do laundry while he hung out with friends. When I complained, my dad would say I was being ungrateful. I left at 19 and never looked back. I met my wife in grad school. She saw how my family treated me and was horrified when I told my parents we were getting engaged at 25. They said she was beneath me, that I was making a mistake. We got married anyway, just her family there. They moved to Florida about eight years ago. Honestly, our relationship only works with distance. We text sometimes, but it's always tense. Last month, my wife and I bought our dream condo, two bedrooms downtown, everything we wanted. We were thrilled but kept it quiet from my parents. They're paying for a storage unit nearby and I knew exactly what would happen if they found out. As far as they knew, we rented a studio near my wife's office. Yesterday afternoon, I was working from home when my college buddy Ryan knocked. Behind him were my parents running like they pulled off a surprise. Ryan ran into them at target and thought it'd be nice to bring them over the moment They walked in and saw our open concept living room, the granite counters, the balcony view. My mom's smile died. She looked around slowly, face getting redder. Then she exploded. She screamed about how selfish we were, all this space and we never offered to help with. She yelled about how we've been getting along so well lately. Why would I lie? She said. I was sneaky and ungrateful, just like always. I stood there frozen. Ryan looked horrified. My mom kept going. Family helps family. You clearly don't care about us. That's when my wife came home. She walked in, saw my mom gesturing wildly, saw my face and her expression hardened. She set down her bag. Stop yelling in our home. My dad quiet until then, face bright red. Your home, he spat. You mean the home my money helped buy? The room went silent. I felt my stomach drop. I turned to face my parents. What money? My mom's angry expression shifted to something smug. She crossed her arms. We've been sending your brother $1,500 every month for eight years to help you both. We assumed he was splitting it like we asked. My wife's jaw dropped. I couldn't breathe. Eight years, $1,500 a month. That's $144,000. My brother bought a boat last year. He went to Japan twice. He drives a Tesla. And I'm standing in my first home that we scraped together for, learning he pocketed money meant for both of us. My hands shook. As I called my brother on speaker.

voice_to_text: Have you ever seen a mountain of meat being built piece by piece? This is how a Turkish donar tower comes to life. The chefs start by slicing beef into thin, even pieces. Not too thick, but not too thin, either. After coating the slices with a special blend of seasonings and letting them marinate, they stack them layer by layer. It's just like building a house. A solid foundation is key to building high and keeping everything perfectly balanced. Sometimes they use tools to press it all tighter. Once the tower reaches a certain height, the chefs begin to shape it, trimming the edges to give it cleaner, more defined. Look, these cuts aren't just for appearance. They help the heat distribute evenly, so the roasted meat comes out crispy on the outside and tender on the inside. And it's not just beef towers. There are chicken ones, too. And each one is made with the same care and patience. But no matter the meat, watching a donor tower being built is surprisingly satisfying. Almost like watching a savory sculpture come to life.

video_description: My father tried to CANCEL my birthday trip because my golden child sister had a RUNNY NOSE...
My family ignored me becoming a lawyer then my brother got arrested and suddenly they needed me.
voice_to_text: My family didn't care when I became a lawyer until my brother got arrested. Then all of a sudden they wanted me again. After I passed the bar exam to become a lawyer. I texted my family the date and time of my swearing and ceremony. My dad replied saying he couldn't make it because my brother Silas had a golf tournament at the same day. My mom said she'd be at the tournament too. Silas sent a laughing emoji and wrote, it's just a ceremony. You already passed. We'll celebrate later. I stared at my phone and typed back, understood. The ceremony was beautiful and I sat there in a room full of new lawyers with their families cheering and taking pictures. I was alone. The woman next to me had her entire extended family there and they kept apologizing for being too loud. I told them it was fine and tried not to cry. Afterwards, the law firm I joined took photos of all the new associates for their website and newsletter. I smiled in my professional headshot and pretended I wasn't heartbroken. My boss pulled me aside and said, where's your family? I wanted to meet them. I said they couldn't make it. And he looked confused but didn't push. I started working criminal defense and I was good at it, really good. I won cases that senior partners said were unwinnable. I worked 80 hour weeks and built a reputation. My family never asked about my Work. At Thanksgiving, my dad spent an hour talking about Silas's promotion at his sales job. And when I mentioned I'd won a major case, he said, that's nice and change the object. Silas asked if I was dating anyone. And when I said I was too busy with work, he said, you're always going to be too busy. That's your problem. My mom nodded and said, he's right. You need balance. I said, I have balance. I'm building a career. My dad laughed and said, Silas has a career and still makes time for family. Maybe you should take notes. On Christmas, my dad gave Silas an expensive watch and gave me a gift card to target. When I opened it, Silas smirked and said, at least you can buy yourself something nice. I left early and my mom texted me later saying I'd ruined Christmas by being dramatic. I stopped going to family dinners. After that, my dad would text saying I was being distant and I needed to make more effort. Didn't respond. My mom called once and said, your father is hurt that you won't come around anymore. Family is supposed to forgive. I said, family is supposed to show up and hung up. Six months after my swearing in ceremony, I got a call from my dad at 2 in the morning. He said, Silas has been arrested. You need to come to the police station right now. I was exhausted from a long day. In court. But I got dressed and drove 40 minutes to the station. Silas had gotten into a bar fight and assaulted someone badly enough to send them to the hospital. The charges were aggravated assault and he was looking at serious prison time. My dad grabbed my arm when I walked in and said, you have to fix this. You're a lawyer. You can make this go away. I said, I'm a criminal defense attorney. I don't make things go away. I defend people in court. He said, so defend him. He's your brother. I looked at Silas sitting in the holding cell and he wouldn't even look at me. My dad said, we're family. You owe us this. I said, I owe you this. Where were you six months ago when I got sworn in? My dad said, this is.

voice_to_text: My wife handed me pills at breakfast. Doctor said, these will help your headaches. She smiled. I'd never mentioned headaches. I pretended to swallow them and had them tested. They came back as poison. That's when I handed the report to my divorce lawyer. The pills sat beside my coffee cup like tiny white threads. Doctor said, these will help your headaches. Claire smiled. Her hand rested on my shoulder. I'd never mentioned headaches. That sweet of you. I picked up the pills. When did you talk to Doctor Morrison? Yesterday. I called about your symptoms. What symptoms? I brought the pills to my mouth, pretended to swallow with orange juice, Tuck them under my tongue. All better, I smiled back. Claire kissed my forehead. Good. Take them every morning, doctor's orders. The moment she left for Pilates, I spit the pills into a napkin. Something was wrong. We've been married three years. Happy, I thought. But lately things felt off. She'd insisted I update my life insurance, $2 million. He suggested I add her name to my investment accounts. She'd started asking about my will. I called my friend Marcus. He's a pharmacist. Can you test something for me quietly? What kind of something? Pills my wife gave me. She says they're for headaches. I don't have. Marcus called me at midnight. David, these aren't headache pills. My stomach dropped. What? What are they? Thallium acetate. It's a poison. Causes organ failure over weeks if you've been taking these daily. His voice was tight. You'd be dead in a month. The room spun. The symptoms look natural, fatigue, nausea, kidney failure. Doctors would think it was cancer. I couldn't breathe. My wife was trying to kill me. I called my lawyer, Richard Chen. He connected me with Catherine Walsh, top divorce attorney in the state. I showed them everything, the pills, Marcus's lab report. We need more, Catherine said. One instance isn't enough. We need a pattern. So I played along. Every morning, Claire handed me pills. Every morning I pretended to take them. I collected them all, 17 pills over 17 days. I also installed cameras, tiny ones, kid bedroom. On day 12, I caught her. She was in the kitchen crushing pills, mixing them into my vitamins, talking on the phone. He's getting weaker. Another few weeks and it'll look natural. The voice on the other end was male. Derek, her yoga instructor. Can't wait to spend his money. Derek said, that house in Malibu is perfect. We'll be there soon. Claire laughed. Once he's gone, I had everything. Catherine called me three days later. I filed the divorce petition this morning. But there's something else you should know. What? Claire's hosting a charity gala tonight at the Fairmont, 200 guests, hospital donors, her nursing colleagues, the mayor supposed to speak. My chest tightened. And I think you should attend. With the police. The Fairmont Ballroom was packed when I arrived. Crystal chandeliers, string Quartet. Claire in a Designer gown. She saw me across the room. Her smile faltered. I walked toward her. Detective Martinez and Detective Chen followed 10 feet behind in plain clothes. David Claire's voice was bright, fake. I didn't know you were coming. Surprise. Her nursing colleagues surrounded us. Her boss, Doctor Patterson, the hospital board president.
